  "prompt": "What are the causes for receding gums?",
  "response": "Receding gums, or gum recession, can be caused by a variety of factors, including:\n\n1. **Periodontal Disease**: This is a major cause of gum recession. Bacterial infections lead to inflammation and loss of the supporting structures of the teeth.\n\n2. **Genetics**: Some individuals may be genetically predisposed to gum disease or have a tendency toward gum recession.\n\n3. **Aggressive Toothbrushing**: Brushing your teeth too hard or using a hard-bristled toothbrush can wear down the gum tissue.\n\n4. **Poor Oral Hygiene**: Inadequate oral hygiene can contribute to plaque buildup, causing inflammation and a higher risk of gum disease.\n\n5. **Hormonal Changes**: Hormonal fluctuations, such as those occurring during pregnancy or menopause, can make gums more sensitive and prone to recession.\n\n6. **Tobacco Use**: Smoking or using other tobacco products can impair gum health and increase the risk of gum disease.\n\n7. **Grinding Teeth (Bruxism)**: Excessive grinding or clenching of teeth can cause the gums to recede due to increased force on the gums and teeth.\n\n8. **Misaligned Teeth or Bite Issues**: Teeth that are misaligned or a bite that is off can put extra pressure on the gums and lead to recession.\n\n9. **Piercings and Oral Jewelry**: Oral piercings can cause tissue damage and lead to gum recession.\n\n10. **Medical Conditions**: Certain diseases such as diabetes and autoimmune disorders can affect gum health.\n\n11. **Nutritional Deficiencies**: Lack of essential nutrients, particularly vitamin C, can impact gum health.\n\nRegular dental check-ups, proper oral hygiene, and awareness of risk factors can help manage and potentially prevent gum recession. If gum recession occurs, it is important to consult a dental professional for appropriate evaluation and treatment.",
